Netic - Considering Full Time
If I stay at Netic:


In the best case, I continue working really hard, getting more and more ownership, but begin to adjust to life. I still don’t really have a personal life, but at least my work life isn’t utter sh*t. Maybe I can go to church consistently and read my Bible each night. Regarding work, I will probably onboard a few clients of my own, begin to own the analytics platform, and work on the evals system. I still do on-call, but don’t freak out every time. In this world, I’m getting paid $140k + 0.2%. Say Netic raises at a $2B valuation before I leave, my ¼ of 0.2% then becomes valued at $1M. Netic probably has 50-100 employees, and I’m highly respected among them. After this, I can come back to school and basically choose what I want to do within the tech world among startups. OpenAI and the like probably aren’t super out of reach either.


In the worst case, it doesn’t get better. My work life continues to be the sh*tshow it has been, and my personal life crumbles. It is no longer just for a summer, but rather for an additional 365 days. My relationship with Maddy is under significant pressure, and it is highly likely I will lose her. I will probably lose contact with all of my friends except a handful, perhaps 3 or so. Netic begins struggling for one reason or another, and every day at work is like hell. I still work 80-100 hours per week, and Melisa outright disrespects me on a weekly basis. Here, either I continue struggling at the cost of my religion, personal life, sanity, friends, girlfriend, family, and mental-physical health OR throw in the towel and go back to school at square 1. At this point the Netic name doesn’t mean much and people look at me just as some other startup kid. Equity becomes virtually worthless and I traded all of this for around $20-50k after taxes and costs. 


If I chose to go back to school:


        In the best case, I get to enjoy my life a bit more, see my friends, family and Maddy. I also get to spend time thinking about what I actually want to do with my life in the tech space or beyond. I get to refocus on my relationship with Christ, the ONLY thing that matters. Perhaps I find a part-time job that allows me to learn and get paid well or get an internship at SpaceX, General Matter, etc. I can do more coffee chats and start exploring my next summer’s opportunity—maybe a top Series A-C startup like Cognition, Cursor, Decagon or a top AI research lab like OpenAI and Anthropic. Here, I am much happier, healthier, and focused. I am a much more intentional person and grateful for the college experience. It truly is the only time in my life where I have no responsibilities and opportunities are essentially endless. Beyond this, I get to go to Hawaii with my friends, New York with Maddy, Brazil with my family at the end of the year and somewhere tropical for Thanksgiving with family + Maddy. What an opportunity. I think the most important of all of these is reconsidering my relationship with Christ and truly seeing what HE wants for my life. 


If as a Christian, I do not put Christ first, then I am doing everything wrong. Logically, Christians should put Christ first no matter what, and that will lead to the best possible life. However, being one foot in one foot out is perhaps the worst of both worlds. You are not truly Christian but also not truly maximizing your worldly life. By being one foot in and one foot out, I am only tricking myself. The joke’s on me. It would be much easier to say F everything and go all in, leaving behind family, friends, morals and subscribing to the capitalistic facade of the American dream. Will true happiness come from this? Hell no. I have not heard one successful founder be satisfied or fulfilled or truly happy. It is always the search for happiness, the striving for fulfillment, that comes out of these people’s mouths. And yet, no one has found it. On the other hand, ‘true’ Christians are the happiest people I know. That’s the life I want. 


Anyways, continuing with this analysis, in the worst case at school I am unhappy, learn nothing and Netic goes crazy. Let’s say I miss out on $10M because Netic became a $20B company. I also am annoyed at classes and don’t really find intellectually stimulating things to do. I still enjoy my life, I still have friends, I still go to the beach and go to all these trips. Life is still amazing. The interesting thing here is, I control most of these things above. My time at school is almost entirely up to my own definition. I can search for interesting things to do, people to meet, and ways to spend my time.


I think it’s clear. Even in the best case at Netic, I prefer the worst case at USC. 


The value of money at a young age.


But ok, let’s say I can make $10M guaranteed at Netic. Does that really matter? How much should money play a part into how I think? I know that it may hurt a bit if I say no and as a result miss out on a lot of money. But realistically, $10M won’t change my life at a young age. Maybe I buy a cool car or take some extravagant vacation, but I still will feel just as confused and lost about what I want to do. No amount of money (ok, maybe under $50M) will change that. I don’t think money should be a consideration. God willing, this will be a rounding error in my life. Money will come as needed. A close friend of mine, David, said something very interesting—Being rich doesn’t make you not a loser. You can be a rich loser and a poor loser.


