A few more questions to consider…
1. Which decision allows me to practice faith, not just believe it?
Honestly, this could go either way. I would have to practice faith under both circumstances. At Netic. I’d have to have faith that God has got my back in this and that everything will be fine. At school, I will have given up this shiny opportunity and will have to have faith that God has my back there too.


2. What path sets me up best to become the man, leader, and Christian I feel called to be?
Honestly, probably going back to school. My faith will most likely slowly dwindle at Netic, especially under the immense pressure at work. At school, I get to reevaluate my life and reprioritize Christ as #1.

3. Am I trading growth for acceleration? Am I solving for speed or depth?
I do think I would be trading growth for acceleration if I go to Netic. My world view still hasn’t fully developed and this may have negative long-term effects (burn out, pessimism, over-reliance on AI, shift in priorities, etc.) that will affect my terminal depth as a person. This is innately a bad trade. 


4. What decision would I make if I knew God would provide either way?
School lol. No question here. By choosing Netic, I’d be choosing to rely on myself a bit more and take (figurative) control of my life. 


5. Am I making this decision out of faith or out of fear (of missing out, falling behind, or being forgotten)?
Probably out of fear (FOMO, etc.) if I go to Netic, but faith if I go to school.




